<head>
<title>Confidence Intervals for Population Proportion p (1 of 4)</title>
    <objref idref="explain_confidence_interval"/>
    <objref idref="find_confidence_intervals"/>
</head>
<body>
    
    
<section>
    <title>Overview</title>
    <body><p>As we mentioned in the introduction to this module, when the variable that we're interested in studying in the population is <em>categorical</em>, the parameter we are trying to infer about is the <em>population proportion (p)</em> associated with that variable. We also learned that the point estimator for the population proportion p is the sample proportion <m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mrow>
<m:mover>
<m:mi>p</m:mi>
<m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
</m:mover>
</m:mrow>
</m:math>.</p>
<p>To refresh your memory, here is a picture that summarizes an example we looked at.</p>
<image style="block" src="../webcontent/image015.gif" alt="A large circle represents the population
of all US Adults. We are interested in the parameter p, the proportion who believe marijuana
should be legalized. From this population we create a sample of size n=1000, represented by a
smaller circle. In this sample, we find that p hat (the point estimator) is .56 . Using point
estimation we estimate p."/>
<p>We are now moving on to interval estimation of p. In other
            words<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092237-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
            we would like to develop a set of intervals
            that<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092246-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
            with different levels of
            confidence<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092249-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
            will capture the value of p. We've actually done all the
            ground<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092415-0500" content=" "?>work
            and discussed all the big ideas of interval estimation when we talked about interval
            estimation for μ, so we'll be able to go through it much faster. Let's begin.</p>
<p>Recall that the general form of any confidence interval for an unknown parameter is:</p>
<p>
<m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mrow>
<m:mi mathvariant="italic">estimate</m:mi>
<m:mo>±</m:mo>
<m:mi mathvariant="italic">margin</m:mi>
<m:mtext> </m:mtext>
<m:mi mathvariant="italic">of</m:mi>
<m:mtext> </m:mtext>
<m:mi mathvariant="italic">error</m:mi>
</m:mrow>
</m:math>
</p>
<p>Since the unknown parameter here is the population proportion p, the point estimator (as I
            reminded you above) is the sample proportion <m:math overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:mover>
                        <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                        <m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
                    </m:mover>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math>. The confidence interval for p,
            therefore<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092507-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
            has the form:</p>
<p>
<m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mrow>
<m:mover>
<m:mi>p</m:mi>
<m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
</m:mover>
<m:mo>±</m:mo>
<m:mi>m</m:mi>
</m:mrow>
</m:math>
</p>
<p>(Recall that m is the notation for the margin of error.) The margin of error
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092519-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>m<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092521-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
            tells us with a certain confidence what the maximum estimation error is that we are
            making, or in other words, that <m:math overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:mover>
                        <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                        <m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
                    </m:mover>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math> is different from p (the parameter it estimates) by no more than m units.</p>
<p>From our previous discussion on confidence intervals, we also know that the margin of error is
            the product of two
            <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092627-0500" comment="use asterisk ather than dot to indicate multiplication in phrase below."?>components:<?oxy_comment_end?></p>
<p>
<m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mrow>
<m:mi>m</m:mi>
<m:mo>=</m:mo>
<m:mi mathvariant="italic">confidence</m:mi>
<m:mtext> </m:mtext>
<m:mi mathvariant="italic">multiplier</m:mi>
<m:mtext> </m:mtext>
<m:mo>⋅</m:mo>
<m:mi mathvariant="italic">SD</m:mi>
<m:mtext> </m:mtext>
<m:mi mathvariant="italic">of</m:mi>
<m:mtext> </m:mtext>
<m:mi mathvariant="italic">the</m:mi>
<m:mtext> </m:mtext>
<m:mi mathvariant="italic">estimator</m:mi>
</m:mrow>
</m:math>
</p>
<p>To figure out what these two components are, we need to go back to a result we obtained in the
            <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092641-0500" content="&quot;"?>Sampling
            Distributions<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092644-0500" content="&quot;"?>
            module of the Probability unit about the sampling distribution of <m:math
                overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:mover>
                        <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                        <m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
                    </m:mover>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math>. We found that under certain conditions (which we'll come back to later),
                <m:math overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:mover>
                        <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                        <m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
                    </m:mover>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math> has a normal distribution with mean p, and standard deviation <m:math
                overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:msqrt>
                        <m:mfrac>
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                                <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                                <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                                <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                                <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
                            </m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                        </m:mfrac>
                    </m:msqrt>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math>. This result makes things very simple for us, because it reveals what the two
            components are that the margin of error is made of:</p>
<p><?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092716-0500" comment="use bullets instead of asterisks"?>*<?oxy_comment_end?>
            Since, like the sampling distribution of <m:math overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:mover>
                        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                    </m:mover>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math>, the sampling distribution of <m:math overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:mover>
                        <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                        <m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
                    </m:mover>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math> is normal, the confidence multipliers that we'll use in the confidence
            interval for p will be the same z* multipliers we use for the confidence interval for μ
            when σ is known (using <em>exactly</em> the same reasoning and the same probability
            results). The multipliers we'll use, then, are: <em>1.645, 2, and 2.576 at the 90%, 95%
                and 99% confidence
                level<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092738-0500"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?>,
                respectively.</em>
        </p>
<p>* The standard deviation of our estimator <m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mrow>
<m:mover>
<m:mi>p</m:mi>
<m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
</m:mover>
</m:mrow>
</m:math> is <m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mrow>
<m:msqrt>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mrow>
<m:mi>p</m:mi>
<m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
<m:mn>1</m:mn>
<m:mo>−</m:mo>
<m:mi>p</m:mi>
<m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:mrow>
<m:mi>n</m:mi>
</m:mfrac>
</m:msqrt>
</m:mrow>
</m:math>
</p>
<p>Putting it all together, we find that the confidence interval for p should be: <m:math
                overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:mover>
                        <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                        <m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
                    </m:mover>
                    <m:mo>±</m:mo>
                    <m:msup>
                        <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>*</m:mo>
                    </m:msup>
                    <m:mo>⋅</m:mo>
                    <m:msqrt>
                        <m:mfrac>
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                                <m:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                    <m:mrow>
                                        <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                                        <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                                        <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                                    </m:mrow>
                                </m:mfenced>
                            </m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                        </m:mfrac>
                    </m:msqrt>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math>. We just have to solve one practical problem and we're done. We're trying to
            estimate the <em>unknown</em> population proportion <em>p</em>, so having it appear in
            the confidence
            interval<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092813-0500" content=" (look!)"?>
            doesn't make any sense. To overcome this problem, we'll do the obvious thing<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092853-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>... </p>
<p>We'll replace p
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092858-0500"?>with<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092857-0500" content="by"?>
            its sample counterpart<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T092932-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
            <m:math overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:mover>
                        <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                        <m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
                    </m:mover>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math>, and work with the <em>standard error of</em>
            <m:math overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:mover>
                        <m:mi> p</m:mi>
                        <m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
                    </m:mover>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math>, <m:math overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:msqrt>
                        <m:mfrac>
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mover>
                                    <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                                    <m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
                                </m:mover>
                                <m:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                    <m:mrow>
                                        <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                                        <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                                        <m:mover>
                                            <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                                            <m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
                                        </m:mover>
                                    </m:mrow>
                                </m:mfenced>
                            </m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                        </m:mfrac>
                    </m:msqrt>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math>.</p>
<p>Now we're done. The confidence interval for the population proportion p is:</p>
<p>
<m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mrow>
<m:mover>
<m:mi>p</m:mi>
<m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
</m:mover>
<m:mo>±</m:mo>
<m:msup>
<m:mi>z</m:mi>
<m:mo>*</m:mo>
</m:msup>
<m:mo>⋅</m:mo>
<m:msqrt>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mrow>
<m:mover>
<m:mi>p</m:mi>
<m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
</m:mover>
<m:mfenced open="(" close=")">
<m:mrow>
<m:mn>1</m:mn>
<m:mo>−</m:mo>
<m:mover>
<m:mi>p</m:mi>
<m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
</m:mover>
</m:mrow>
</m:mfenced>
</m:mrow>
<m:mi>n</m:mi>
</m:mfrac>
</m:msqrt>
</m:mrow>
</m:math>
</p>
<p>As you'll see from the examples we'll present in this unit, estimating the population proportion comes up a lot in the context of polls.</p></body></section>
